Process Document – Monitoring and Managing
Aging Pending Sub-Issues
Model Risk Management Committee (MRMC) | MRO Workstream
1. Purpose
This document provides a detailed, step-by-step process for the identification, monitoring, and management of aging pending Sub-Issues within the Model Risk Management Committee (MRMC) framework. The goal is to ensure that all Sub-Issues approaching or exceeding their target remediation timelines are systematically identified, escalated as appropriate, and resolved in accordance with the Enterprise Issues Management Policy (RMO-EORM-EIM-1000) and internal audit requirements.
This process supports the quarterly Sub-Issue review obligations of the MRO team and ensures timely reporting to MRMC stakeholders.
2. Scope
In Scope:
•All Sub-Issues in the MRM Issue/Sub-Issue inventory system in SNOW that are currently in a Pending state and have not been actioned within defined aging thresholds.
•Sub-Issues linked to both active and retired models where remediation deadlines are approaching or overdue.
•Sub-Issues in "Remediation in Progress", "Draft", and "Pending Review" states that have exceeded their expected due dates.
•Sub-Issues flagged during quarterly reviews by Model Validation Leads and MRO for thematic analysis.
Out of Scope:
•Sub-Issues that are formally closed with documented closure rationale.
•Issues (as distinct from Sub-Issues) managed under the formal Issue escalation process.
3. Roles and Responsibilities
•MRO Team (Model Risk Oversight): Responsible for pulling the aging Sub-Issue register from SNOW, performing initial analysis, and distributing reports on a weekly and quarterly basis.
•Model Validation Leads: Responsible for performing the initial quarterly lookback on the full and closed Sub-Issue populations. Also accountable for Sub-Issue identification within 30 days of item identification per policy.
•Chief Model Risk Officer (CMRO) or Delegate: Responsible for creating and maintaining the quarterly review approach document; serves as approver for the Sub-Issue quarterly review and thematic analysis.
•Model Governance Teammates: Responsible for pulling Sub-Issue listings on a quarterly basis and preparing Sub-Issue reporting to MRMC using the EIM reporting template.
•RMO Governance and Controls Office (GCO): Reviews and challenges Sub-Issue reporting materials prior to MRMC presentation.
4. Process Steps
Step 1: Extract the Aging Pending Sub-Issue Register from SNOW
Obtain the latest Sub-Issue inventory extract from the MRM Issue/Sub-Issue system in SNOW. The extract should include the following fields:
oMRM Issue/Sub-Issue ID
oInventory Number (DINV Identifier)
oDesignation
oIssue/Sub-Issue Name
oStatus
oIssue/Sub-Issue Owner
oArcher Finding/Sub-Issue Selection
oIdentified By
oMRM Issue/Sub-Issue Category
oIssue/Sub-Issue Due Date
oMRM Pending Date
oMRM Issue/Sub-Issue Close Date
oValidation Task ID
oValidation Type
oUpdated
oUpdated By
oUpdated By User
oClosed By
•Filter the extract to include only Sub-Issues currently in "Pending" state, including Pending Review, Pending Closure, and other pending sub-statuses.
Step 2: Apply Aging Thresholds and Classify Sub-Issues
Using the MRM Pending Date and/or Issue/Sub-Issue Due Date fields, calculate the number of days each Sub-Issue has remained in Pending status. Classify Sub-Issues into the following aging buckets:
•0–30 days: Within standard remediation window. No escalation required; monitor.
•31–60 days: Approaching threshold. Flag for awareness; prompt Sub-Issue owner for status update.
•61–90 days: At risk. Escalate to Model Validation Lead; document reason for delay.
•90+ days: Overdue. Require CMRO or delegate review; include in MRMC reporting. Assess if Sub-Issue should be elevated to an Issue.
Step 3: Weekly Monitoring and Tracking
•The MRO team is responsible for refreshing the aging Sub-Issue tracker on a weekly basis using the latest SNOW extract.
•Changes in Sub-Issue status (e.g., closures, re-openings, owner reassignments) must be captured and noted in the tracker.
•Please refer to the Sub-Issues Aging Tracker Excel file for the sample inventory and tracking template.
•The team is required to prepare the attached aging summary report format for leadership review.
Step 4: Quarterly Sub-Issue Review
On a quarterly basis, the following activities are performed in accordance with Section 2.2.8 of the MRMC Policy Procedure:
•Full Population Review: Pull the complete population of Sub-Issues that are "not closed" as of the quarter-end date (or last business day of the quarter-end month). Include Issue/Sub-Issue determinations and supporting rationales or Issue Finding IDs.
•Closed Population Review: Pull all Sub-Issues closed within the last 12 months for completeness assessment.
•Thematic Analysis: Model Validation Leads perform a lookback on the full and closed populations to identify themes and trends. Determine whether any Sub-Issues in aggregate rise to the level of an Issue.
•Narrative Document: Prepare a quarterly approach document outlining: process for obtaining the Sub-Issue Register, rationale for completeness and accuracy, support for aggregated analysis, and stakeholders engaged in the review. The CMRO or delegate is responsible for creating and maintaining this document.
•Approval: The CMRO or delegate serves as the approver for the quarterly review output.
Step 5: Escalation and Issue Elevation Assessment
•Where aging Sub-Issues (90+ days) show persistent non-remediation or repeated patterns across multiple models, the MRO team must assess whether aggregation warrants formal Issue elevation.
•Escalations are to be documented and tracked in the quarterly narrative document with rationale for escalation decisions.
•Issue elevation follows the guidelines within the Issue/Sub-Issue Designation section of the MRMC Policy Procedure and the Enterprise Issues Management Policy (RMO-EORM-EIM-1000).
Step 6: Reporting to MRMC
•Utilizing the EIM reporting template, Model Governance Teammates prepare Sub-Issue reporting for submission to MRMC.
•Reporting materials must be reviewed and challenged by the RMO Governance and Controls Office (GCO) prior to MRMC presentation.
•The CMRO or delegate serves as the reviewer and approver of Sub-Issue reporting to MRMC.
•Aging Sub-Issue trends and any escalations/Issue elevations must be explicitly highlighted in MRMC reporting materials.
5. Policy Reference
This process document is prepared in alignment with the following policy and procedure references:
•RMO-EORM-EIM-1000 – Enterprise Issues Management Policy
•MRMC Policy Procedure Section 2.2.8 – Sub-Issue Identification, Quarterly Reviews, and Reporting
•Issue/Sub-Issue Designation guidelines as defined within the MRMC Policy Procedure
6. Document Control
Document Owner: MRO Team / Model Governance
Review Frequency: Quarterly (aligned with Sub-Issue quarterly review cycle)
Approver: Chief Model Risk Officer or Delegate
Distribution: MRMC members, MRO Team, Model Validation Leads, RMO GCO
Classification: Confidential – Internal Use Only
